body:
### Environment

Node version: v16.14.0
npm version: 8.3.1
Local ESLint version: `main` branch
Global ESLint version: 
Operating System: windows


### What parser are you using?

Default (Espree)

### What did you do?

While working on https://github.com/eslint/espree/pull/577, where we switched from `eslint-plugin-node` to `eslint-plugin-n`, I noticed that vscode-eslint extension (set to use FlatESLint) crashes, and therefore doesn't show any lint messages, when I open a file that has directives with now-unknown `node/*` rules. For example, `// eslint-disable-next-line node/no-unsupported-features/es-syntax`:

```
[Error - 11:54:29 PM] TypeError: Could not find the rule "node/no-unsupported-features/es-syntax".
    at FlatESLint.getRulesMetaForResults (C:\milos\espree\node_modules\eslint\lib\eslint\flat-eslint.js:720:27)

```

This doesn't happen when vscode-eslint is using the `ESLint` class.

To reproduce this difference in behavior, I wrote a script that runs `lintText` and then `getRulesMetaForResults`, as IDE integrations do.

<details>
<summary>Configuration</summary>

```
No config file needed
```
</details>

```js
const { LegacyESLint, FlatESLint } = require("eslint/use-at-your-own-risk");
const assert = require("assert");

(async () => {
    const text = "/* eslint-disable foo */";

    const legacyESLint = new LegacyESLint({ useEslintrc: false });
    const legacyResults = await legacyESLint.lintText(text);
    assert.strictEqual(legacyResults[0].messages.length, 1);
    assert.strictEqual(legacyResults[0].messages[0].ruleId, "foo");
    legacyESLint.getRulesMetaForResults(legacyResults); // does not throw

    const flatESLint = new FlatESLint({ overrideConfigFile: true });
    const flatResults = await flatESLint.lintText(text);
    assert.strictEqual(flatResults[0].messages.length, 1);
    assert.strictEqual(flatResults[0].messages[0].ruleId, "foo");
    try {
        flatESLint.getRulesMetaForResults(flatResults);
    } catch(e) {
        console.log("Throws!");
        console.log(e);
    }
})();

```


### What did you expect to happen?

`FlatESLint#getRulesMetaForResults` to have the same behavior as `ESLint#getRulesMetaForResults`: not throw on unknown rules.

### What actually happened?

```
Throws!
TypeError: Could not find the rule "foo".
    at FlatESLint.getRulesMetaForResults (C:\milos\eslint\lib\eslint\flat-eslint.js:720:27)
    at C:\milos\eslint\test.js:18:20
```

### Link to Minimal Reproducible Example

https://github.com/eslint/eslint/tree/getrulesmeta-issue-repro

### Participation

- [X] I am willing to submit a pull request for this issue.

### Additional comments

It's debatable whether lint messages that report unknown rules should really have those rules set as `ruleId`, but that looks like a bigger change.
